               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-220-person1924">
                  MARY 
                  HUGHES
               <interp inst="t18270913-220-person1924" type="surname" value="HUGHES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-220-person1924" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-220-person1924" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Patrick Hughes; we live in <placeName id="t18270913-220-crimeloc1242">Union-place, Chelsea</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18270913-220-crimeloc1242" type="placeName" value="Union-place, Chelsea"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18270913-220-crimeloc1242" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-220-off1240 t18270913-220-crimeloc1242"></join>. On the 15th of July these articles were in our back parlour and front kitchen. I went out that evening at eight o'clock; I returned at twelve, and the watchman gave me information. I knew the prisoner, but had not seen her for four years.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-220-person1925">
                  MARY 
                  HUGHES
               <interp inst="t18270913-220-person1925" type="surname" value="HUGHES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-220-person1925" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-220-person1925" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the prosecutrix's daughter. The prisoner came to our house that evening, and sent me out three times for a young woman whom she knew. I did not go far the first time, but came back and said I did not see her. I went as far as the Star and Garter public-house the second time; and the third time, as I returned, I met the prisoner with a bundle in my mother's red handkerchief - this was a little after eight o'clock; she asked if I had seen the woman - I said Yes. I went home and missed the things, which were safe when I went out.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-220-person1926">
                  JOHN 
                  CANNEY
               <interp inst="t18270913-220-person1926" type="surname" value="CANNEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-220-person1926" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-220-person1926" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 15th of July, I was in the back room of this house where I lodge; the prisoner came in and told a young man and I, who were writing a letter, to come into the front room, as we should be quiet - we did so, and in a few minutes we came into the front room. I saw her tying up a bundle - I knew nothing of her before; she brought the bundle, and put something on my box. I went up stairs, and as I came down, saw her going out - I followed and enquired for her.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-220-person1927">
                  JANE 
                  ROBERTS
               <interp inst="t18270913-220-person1927" type="surname" value="ROBERTS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-220-person1927" type="given" value="JANE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-220-person1927" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a publican. On the evening of Sunday, the 15th of July, the prisoner came and asked me to let her leave this bundle in my bar, which I did. I gave it to Allen.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-220-person1928">
                  WILLIAM 
                  ALLEN
               <interp inst="t18270913-220-person1928" type="surname" value="ALLEN"></interp>
